</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="85" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="85">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="85">
The genus is characterized by fastigium of vertex compressed, narrower than first antennal segment, eyes circular, prominent, pronotum markedly selliform with posterior part of lateral lobes strongly inflated, surface smooth and matt, fore coxae may be armed with a small spine or not, femora unarmed, fore tibiae with open tympana on each side, fore wings reduced to short lobes, hind wings vestigial. The male mid tibiae have a much enlarged and up-curved ventral spur, its first tarsal segment is greatly enlarged, more than twice as that of fore legs, the female has not the inflated pronotum and is lacking spurs on mid tarsi (
<bibRefCitation author="Rehn, JAG" journalOrPublisher="Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der Deutschen Zentral-Afrika-Expedition, 1907 - 1908" pageId="14" pageNumber="91" pagination="1 - 229" title="Orthoptera I. Mantidae, Phasmidae, Acrididae, Tettigonidae und Gryllidae aus dem Zentral-Afrikanischenseengebiet, Uganda und dem Ituri-Becken des Kongo." volume="5" year="1914">Rehn 1914</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ragge, DR" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin British Museum (Natural History) Entomology" pageId="14" pageNumber="91" pagination="1 - 192" title="A review of the African Phaneropterinae with open tympana (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae)." url="http://www.archive.org/details/bulletinofbritis40entolond" volume="40" year="1980">Ragge 1980</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
